05518nam a22006855i 9780774851855DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072003xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748518557 a10.59962/97807748518552doi  a(DE-B1597)661400  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHQ1781.G46 2003eb 7aSOC0320002bisacsh04a305.4200aGender and Change in Hong Kong :bGlobalization, Postcolonialism, and Chinese Patriarchy /ced. by Eliza Wing-Yee Lee. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b7 tables, 1 illustration  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContemporary Chinese Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Gender and Change in Hong Kong -- tEngendering a Legal System: The Unique Challenge of Postcolonial Hong Kong -- tWomen’s Activism during Hong Kong’s Political Transition -- tIndividualism and Patriarchy: The Identity of Entrepreneurial Women Lawyers in Hong Kong -- tWithering Away of the Hong Kong Dream? Women Workers under Industrial Restructuring -- tDiscourse on Baau Yih Naai (Keeping Concubines): Questions of Citizenship and Identity in Postcolonial Hong Kong -- tNegotiating Gender Identity: Postcolonialism and Hong Kong Christian Women -- tEmpowering Mobility: “Astronaut” Women in Australia -- tProspects for the Development of a Critical Feminist Discourse -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe 1980s and 1990s represent a critical historical juncture for Hong Kong, as it underwent important social, political, and economic transformations. This period of transition, during which the state worked to redefine itself, significantly altered the role and status of Hong Kong women. Colonial modernity, which arose through the integration of the colonial state, the capitalist economy, and the Hong Kong Chinese society, proved favourable for some women but also had adverse consequences for others. It constructed women of different class interests and shaped the gendered citizenship of its colonial subjects. Gender and Change in Hong Kong analyzes women's changing identities and agencies amidst the complex interaction of three important forces, namely, globalization, postcolonialism, and Chinese patriarchy. The chapters examine the issues from a number of perspectives to consider legal changes, political participation, the situation of working-class and professional women, sexuality, religion, and international migration. This incisive volume offers sophisticated theoretical discussions and original empirical findings, and will appeal to a wide range of scholars and students in gender and women's studies, postcolonialism, globalization, and Asian studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPatriarchyzChinazHong Kong. 0aPostcolonialismzChinazHong Kong. 0aWomen in developmentzChinazHong Kong. 0aWomenzChinazHong KongxEconomic conditions. 0aWomenzChinazHong KongxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aChiu, Stephen Wing-Kai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischler, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Eliza W.Y., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Eliza Wing-Yee, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLee¹, Ching-Kwan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPetersen, Carole J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTarn, Siumi Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWong, Wai-Ching, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov